Class FilePath

Direct Known Subclasses:
NetworkPath
public class FilePath extends ResourcePath
An abstraction for a path on any kind of filesystem or file-related data source.

This class contains numerous methods which down-cast the return value of the superclass to make use easier for clients. Methods that are unique to this class mainly have to do with filesystems:

  • absolute() - This file path as an absolute path
  • asFile() - This file path as a file
  • asStringPath() - This file path without any root or scheme
  • asUnixString() - This file path as a forward-slash separated string
  • file(FileName) - This file path with the given filename appended
  • ResourcePath.hasScheme() - True if this filepath has a scheme as in s3://telenav/README.md
  • isCurrentFolder() - True if this filepath is the current folder's filepath
  • ResourcePath.schemes() - List of schemes for this filepath, or an empty list if there are none
  • withoutSchemes() - This filepath without any scheme

Parsing

  • parseFilePath(Listener listener, String, Object...) - The given string as a file path

Factories

  • filePath(URI) - A file path for the given URI
  • filePath(java.io.File) - A file path for the given File
  • filePath(java.nio.file.Path) - A file path for the given Java NIO path
  • filePath(FileName) - A filepath with only the given filename in it
  • filePath(StringPath) - The given string path as a file path
Author:
jonathanl (shibo)

      Overrides:
      subpath in class ResourcePath
      Returns:
      The sub-path of this path starting at given start index (inclusive) and extending to the end index (exclusive). If start and end are equal, the empty path is returned. If start and end are not equal and the path is absolute, the sub-path will still be absolute with the same root. If the start and end indexes are invalid, null is returned.
